pters of The Second Scroll mirror the books of the Pentateuch (the 'first scroll') and the language is rich with biblical, talmudic, kabbalistic, and literary allusions as both the narrator and his uncle wrestle with the meaning of Jewish identity, messianic faith, and homecoming.Popham and Pollock's scholarly edition re-creates the feel of the Knopf publication of 1951-now a collector's item-but restores the text to Klein's original vision. This includes echoing the architectural structure of the Sistine Chapel in the physical layout of 'Gloss Gimel,' Klein's powerful commentary on Michelangelo's famous ceiling. Extensive annotations, and appendices that cross-reference the finished book to the raw material gathered during the author's trip to Israel and to the fund-raising speeches he delivered on his return, give the reader access to the process by which the novel took shape. A significant addition to UTP's Collected Works of A.M. Klein, and of interest not only to Klein scholars, The Second Scroll marks the inception of Holocaust literature and holds a central place in the Canadian literary canon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aCanadianszIsraelvFiction. 0aHolocaust survivorsvFiction. 0aJewsvLiterary collections. 0aJudaismvLiterary collections. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aPollock, Zailig, eeditor.1 aPopham, Elizabeth A., eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442682320423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682320.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eB